WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.520
All right, it's 11.05.

00:11.520 --> 00:14.560
I'm going to try to start promptly at 11.05 each time.

00:14.560 --> 00:16.080
So welcome.

00:16.080 --> 00:17.800
Has everybody psyched?

00:17.800 --> 00:20.040
I'm psyched.

00:20.040 --> 00:22.200
This is 9.13, the human brain.

00:22.200 --> 00:23.240
I'm Nancy Canwisher.

00:23.240 --> 00:25.280
I'm the prof for this class.

00:25.280 --> 00:28.080
Unless you were wondering, I have a brain.

00:28.080 --> 00:28.880
And there it is.

00:28.880 --> 00:31.240
That's me with some bits colored in

00:31.240 --> 00:34.840
that you will learn about in this class.

00:34.840 --> 00:36.240
What I'm going to do today is I'm

00:36.240 --> 00:39.720
going to tell you a brief story for around 10 minutes.

00:39.720 --> 00:43.280
And then I'm going to talk about the why, how, and what

00:43.280 --> 00:46.440
of studying the human brain, why it's a cool thing to do,

00:46.440 --> 00:48.360
how you do it, and what in particular we're

00:48.360 --> 00:50.240
going to learn about in here.

00:50.240 --> 00:52.120
And then we'll do some mechanics and details

00:52.120 --> 00:54.560
of the course and allocation of grades and all that.

00:54.560 --> 00:56.800
It's on the syllabus anyway.

00:56.800 --> 00:58.000
Cool?

00:58.000 --> 01:00.640
That's the agenda.

01:00.640 --> 01:01.520
All right.

01:01.520 --> 01:04.360
So let's start with that story.

01:04.360 --> 01:09.840
And for this, I'm going to set up here.

01:09.840 --> 01:11.400
The story isn't that long, but it has

01:11.400 --> 01:13.440
a lot of interesting little weird bits.

01:13.440 --> 01:15.960
So I have cue cards to remind myself of all the bits

01:15.960 --> 01:18.480
I want to remember to say.

01:18.480 --> 01:21.240
So you can put away your phones and your computers,

01:21.240 --> 01:22.480
and you don't need to take notes.

01:22.480 --> 01:24.720
This is just a story.

01:24.720 --> 01:27.400
It's going to foreshadow a lot of the themes in the course,

01:27.400 --> 01:31.320
but it's not stuff you're going to be tested on.

01:31.320 --> 01:34.640
So this is a true story.

01:34.640 --> 01:38.080
And I've changed only a few tiny little bits

01:38.080 --> 01:41.040
to protect the identity of the people involved.

01:41.040 --> 01:44.560
But otherwise, it's an absolutely true story.

01:44.560 --> 01:47.720
It's a story about a scary medical situation

01:47.720 --> 01:50.960
that happened to a friend of mine a few years ago.

01:50.960 --> 01:53.200
But at the same time, it's a story

01:53.200 --> 01:55.520
about the nature of the human mind,

01:55.520 --> 01:59.680
about the organization of the human brain.

01:59.680 --> 02:05.160
And it's also a story about the ability or lack thereof

02:05.160 --> 02:07.880
to recover after brain damage.

02:07.880 --> 02:15.360
It's also, incidentally, a story about resilience, privilege,

02:15.360 --> 02:17.560
expertise, and all of those things

02:17.560 --> 02:23.800
that are characteristic of many people in Cambridge society.

02:23.840 --> 02:29.160
Not so relevant for the course, but all right, here goes.

02:29.160 --> 02:32.160
So a few years ago, a friend of mine

02:32.160 --> 02:34.200
was staying over at my house in Cambridge,

02:34.200 --> 02:37.600
en route to a conference in a nearby state.

02:37.600 --> 02:42.120
And this guy, I'll call him Bob, was a close friend of mine.

02:42.120 --> 02:45.320
I'd known him for years and years.

02:45.320 --> 02:46.560
We talked regularly.

02:46.560 --> 02:48.640
We went on hiking trips together.

02:48.640 --> 02:50.360
We were pretty close.

02:50.360 --> 02:52.040
So he's en route to this conference.

02:52.040 --> 02:55.800
He's staying over at my house the night before.

02:55.800 --> 02:58.920
And the plan was for him to get up early the next morning

02:58.920 --> 03:00.040
and drive to the conference.

03:00.040 --> 03:02.840
So we hung out the night before and chatted.

03:02.840 --> 03:05.440
And the next morning, he's sleeping in the next room

03:05.440 --> 03:06.840
over from mine.

03:06.840 --> 03:09.640
And early in the morning, I hear some shuffling.

03:09.640 --> 03:12.360
I think, yep, OK, Bob is packing to leave.

03:12.360 --> 03:14.000
And thank god, I don't need to get up.

03:14.000 --> 03:15.840
I'm only dimly awake.

03:15.840 --> 03:18.560
And so I'm not paying that much attention.

03:18.560 --> 03:20.400
Shuffle, shuffle, shuffle in the background.

03:22.160 --> 03:23.160
And then I hear a crash.

03:26.440 --> 03:29.400
And I think, what the hell is that?

03:29.400 --> 03:32.920
And I get up, and I go into the next room.

03:32.920 --> 03:36.680
And Bob is lying on the floor, not moving.

03:36.680 --> 03:38.280
I say, Bob.

03:38.280 --> 03:40.160
And there's no answer.

03:40.160 --> 03:42.400
And then I shout, Bob.

03:42.400 --> 03:44.240
And there's no answer.

03:44.240 --> 03:47.400
And then I dialed 911.

03:47.400 --> 03:50.280
While we were sitting there waiting for the ambulance

03:50.320 --> 03:53.760
to arrive, Bob starts to wake up.

03:53.760 --> 03:56.200
And he's very woozy, but he's alive.

03:56.200 --> 03:58.800
And he's making a little bit of sense.

03:58.800 --> 04:00.720
And he can't figure out what's going on.

04:00.720 --> 04:02.520
And neither can I.

04:02.520 --> 04:05.040
And so we're talking and chatting.

04:05.040 --> 04:07.680
And he's making a little more sense.

04:07.680 --> 04:10.200
But we still know what's happening.

04:10.200 --> 04:13.640
So then the ambulance arrives incredibly fast.

04:13.640 --> 04:15.120
So like three minutes, boom.

04:15.120 --> 04:18.560
There's three EMTs rushing in the front door, rushing up

04:18.560 --> 04:20.280
to the room where Bob was.

04:20.280 --> 04:22.480
And they take all his vitals.

04:22.480 --> 04:25.080
And they can't find anything wrong.

04:25.080 --> 04:27.000
And so they're really casual.

04:27.000 --> 04:29.640
I guess they confront stuff like this all the time.

04:29.640 --> 04:30.640
I don't.

04:30.640 --> 04:31.800
Bob doesn't.

04:31.800 --> 04:33.440
But they're very calm about it.

04:33.440 --> 04:36.440
And they're saying, well, you could take him to the hospital

04:36.440 --> 04:38.720
or not.

04:38.720 --> 04:41.560
And I was like, I think we need to know what just happened.

04:41.560 --> 04:42.920
Even though he seems OK, we kind of

04:42.920 --> 04:45.520
need to know what this is all about, don't you think?

04:45.520 --> 04:48.320
They're like, yeah, you could take him to the ER.

04:48.320 --> 04:51.560
And I said, well, do we need to waste ambulance resources?

04:51.560 --> 04:53.720
Or do you think it's safe if I drive him myself,

04:53.720 --> 04:55.400
since there's a hospital not far away?

04:55.400 --> 04:57.760
They said, you could drive him yourself.

04:57.760 --> 05:01.240
So I drive Bob to the Mount Auburn Hospital

05:01.240 --> 05:04.400
ER, which is less than a mile from my house.

05:04.400 --> 05:06.480
And we do the usual ER thing, which is mostly

05:06.480 --> 05:08.320
waiting and waiting and waiting.

05:08.320 --> 05:09.920
But various docs come by.

05:09.920 --> 05:11.360
And they take all these tests.

05:11.360 --> 05:13.520
And they take all these history questions.

05:13.520 --> 05:14.280
And it goes on and on.

05:14.280 --> 05:17.680
And basically, they're just not finding anything.

05:17.680 --> 05:19.600
So after about an hour or two of this,

05:19.600 --> 05:20.640
they're still doing tests.

05:20.640 --> 05:22.080
They don't want to quite let him go yet,

05:22.080 --> 05:23.720
because they don't know what happened.

05:23.720 --> 05:25.720
Everybody's calm about it.

05:25.720 --> 05:27.440
I figure, OK, fine.

05:27.440 --> 05:29.520
I got work to do.

05:29.520 --> 05:33.080
And I tell Bob, text me throughout the day.

05:33.080 --> 05:37.240
And I'll come get you whenever they're ready to release you.

05:37.240 --> 05:41.040
And so I go into work.

05:41.040 --> 05:43.280
But just before I go into work, a thought

05:43.280 --> 05:45.040
flashes through my mind.

05:45.040 --> 05:51.640
And I say to the ER doc, you should check Bob's brain.

05:51.640 --> 05:54.240
And the reason that thought flashed through my mind

05:54.240 --> 05:57.520
is that, actually, I had been worrying about Bob

05:57.520 --> 05:59.040
for a number of years.

05:59.040 --> 06:02.280
And it hadn't quite registered consciously.

06:02.280 --> 06:04.440
I hadn't was kind of too horrifying a thought for me

06:04.440 --> 06:07.080
to really allow myself to realize

06:07.080 --> 06:08.640
I was worried about Bob's brain.

06:08.640 --> 06:10.600
But I was worried about a very particular thing.

06:10.600 --> 06:14.360
And that is that Bob had been showing these weird signs

06:14.360 --> 06:19.520
that he often got lost and didn't know where he was.

06:19.520 --> 06:21.680
And on the one hand, this just didn't make any sense,

06:21.680 --> 06:24.520
because he was fine in every other way.

06:24.520 --> 06:26.280
But it was really pretty striking.

06:26.280 --> 06:29.720
So one time, I was over at Bob's house

06:29.720 --> 06:31.640
with some other friends of ours.

06:31.640 --> 06:35.600
And the friend asked Bob, how do I drive from your house

06:35.600 --> 06:37.080
into Cambridge?

06:37.080 --> 06:39.280
And Bob said, well, you go to the end of the driveway,

06:39.280 --> 06:40.960
and you turn left.

06:40.960 --> 06:45.600
My friend and I looked at each other like, Bob.

06:45.600 --> 06:46.280
What?

06:46.280 --> 06:47.680
And Bob thinks about it for a minute, yeah,

06:47.680 --> 06:50.240
end of the driveway, turn left.

06:50.240 --> 06:53.880
I just had this sinking feeling of dread

06:53.880 --> 06:56.400
in the pit of my stomach.

06:56.400 --> 06:59.120
But we sort of made light of it and made fun of it.

06:59.120 --> 06:59.920
And it went by.

06:59.920 --> 07:01.200
It was like, no, you turn right.

07:01.200 --> 07:03.520
And we gave the directions.

07:03.520 --> 07:06.440
Another time, a friend of mine was driving with Bob

07:06.440 --> 07:08.400
in Bob's hometown.

07:08.400 --> 07:11.800
And noticed that Bob didn't seem to know

07:11.800 --> 07:15.080
how to get to the grocery store in his hometown, where

07:15.080 --> 07:18.040
he'd lived for a really long time.

07:18.040 --> 07:22.320
And a trip he'd made hundreds of times.

07:22.320 --> 07:26.120
Another time, I was at a conference in Germany.

07:26.120 --> 07:29.720
And I saw these arrays of posters of people

07:29.720 --> 07:32.600
presenting usually pretty dry scientific things.

07:32.600 --> 07:35.440
And out of the corner of my eye, I see the title of a poster.

07:35.440 --> 07:39.960
And it says, navigational deficits, colon, and early sign

07:39.960 --> 07:41.400
of Alzheimer's.

07:41.400 --> 07:42.280
And I saw that.

07:42.280 --> 07:44.480
And I just thought, oh.

07:44.480 --> 07:47.280
And I just kind of suppressed the thought.

07:47.280 --> 07:49.960
And I thought, oh my god, Bob wasn't that old.

07:49.960 --> 07:52.480
I know Alzheimer's can very rarely strike early.

07:52.480 --> 07:53.960
I didn't want to think about it.

07:53.960 --> 07:59.160
But it was like rattling around in the back of my consciousness.

07:59.160 --> 08:01.240
So there had been these signs.

08:01.240 --> 08:03.160
But as I say, they didn't make sense.

08:03.200 --> 08:06.960
Because Bob was holding down a very high-powered job.

08:06.960 --> 08:09.120
He was writing beautiful prose.

08:09.120 --> 08:11.240
He was the life of every party he was at.

08:11.240 --> 08:16.800
Witty, funny, everybody's favorite life of the party.

08:16.800 --> 08:18.320
So how could that be?

08:18.320 --> 08:20.320
It just didn't make sense that there would be anything

08:20.320 --> 08:22.080
wrong with Bob's brain.

08:22.080 --> 08:24.920
So I managed for a few years to notice these signs

08:24.920 --> 08:27.080
and ignore them and not pay any attention.

08:33.520 --> 08:40.160
So the killer thing is I should have known better.

08:40.160 --> 08:43.240
My research for the last 20 years

08:43.240 --> 08:45.200
has been on the very fact that there

08:45.200 --> 08:48.760
are different parts of the brain that do different things.

08:48.760 --> 08:51.040
And one of the corollaries of that

08:51.040 --> 08:53.680
is you can have a problem with one of those parts,

08:53.680 --> 08:56.000
and the other parts can work just fine.

08:56.000 --> 08:59.600
And so I, if anyone, should have realized, yes,

08:59.600 --> 09:02.280
there's something really wrong with Bob's navigation

09:02.280 --> 09:03.320
abilities.

09:03.320 --> 09:06.520
And the fact that he's smart, and witty, and funny,

09:06.520 --> 09:08.560
and holding down a high-powered job

09:08.560 --> 09:11.440
doesn't mean there isn't something wrong with his brain,

09:11.440 --> 09:14.080
with a part of his brain.

09:14.080 --> 09:16.920
But I didn't realize that.

09:16.920 --> 09:21.240
But then, as I'm leaving the ER, it kind of all clicked.

09:21.240 --> 09:26.000
And I said to the ER doc, you better check his brain.

09:26.000 --> 09:28.080
I thought Bob was out of earshot when I said that.

09:28.080 --> 09:28.680
He heard it.

09:28.680 --> 09:29.880
He's like, what?

09:29.880 --> 09:32.520
I was like, oh, never mind.

09:32.520 --> 09:35.200
Anyway, the ER doc, with the kind of confidence

09:35.200 --> 09:38.960
that only docs can muster, said, no, not a brain thing.

09:38.960 --> 09:44.120
This is a hard thing, which wasn't exactly reassuring.

09:44.120 --> 09:48.640
But I set aside the brain thought, and I went off to work.

09:51.560 --> 09:57.440
So throughout the day, I texted with Bob a few times.

09:58.080 --> 09:59.200
Things seemed to be fine.

09:59.200 --> 10:00.120
They'd done more tests.

10:00.120 --> 10:02.080
They weren't find anything.

10:02.080 --> 10:04.040
We just got calmer and calmer about it.

10:04.040 --> 10:05.880
I guess sometimes weird stuff happens,

10:05.880 --> 10:08.160
and you just move on.

10:08.160 --> 10:11.520
But then that night, around 7 or 8 at night,

10:11.520 --> 10:14.520
I was over at a friend's house, and the phone rang.

10:14.520 --> 10:15.800
And it was Bob.

10:15.800 --> 10:20.000
I picked it up, and Bob says, get over here.

10:20.000 --> 10:23.200
They found something in my brain.

10:23.200 --> 10:25.720
So I ran out of the house, grabbed my phone,

10:25.720 --> 10:29.720
and as I'm driving to the Mount Auburn ER,

10:29.720 --> 10:34.360
I called my trusty lab tech, an amazing guy who

10:34.360 --> 10:37.160
keeps track of all kinds of things much better than I do.

10:37.160 --> 10:41.880
And I said, I remember that we scanned Bob a bunch of years

10:41.880 --> 10:45.000
ago for a regular experiment in my lab.

10:45.000 --> 10:46.080
And I don't remember.

10:46.080 --> 10:49.280
The date, I don't remember anything about it,

10:49.280 --> 10:52.440
but dig around in the files and see if you can figure it out.

10:52.440 --> 10:56.360
It might be useful to have that scan.

10:56.360 --> 10:59.360
So by the time I get to the ER, my lab tech

10:59.360 --> 11:02.960
has already texted me back and said, found the scans.

11:02.960 --> 11:05.640
I'm putting them in a drop box for you.

11:05.640 --> 11:09.600
So I go into the ER, and there's Bob in the ER doc.

11:09.600 --> 11:15.840
And Bob says to me, do you want to see it?

11:15.840 --> 11:18.440
The ER doc, the radiologist, has already

11:18.440 --> 11:21.040
shown Bob the picture of his brain.

11:21.040 --> 11:25.400
And so they take me in there, and I look at it, and I gulped.

11:25.400 --> 11:27.960
There was a thing the size of a lime smack

11:27.960 --> 11:31.080
in the middle of his brain.

11:31.080 --> 11:33.480
Pretty terrifying.

11:33.480 --> 11:42.400
So this lime in the middle of Bob's brain

11:42.400 --> 11:45.440
was right next to a region that my lab had studied

11:45.440 --> 11:46.680
in great detail.

11:46.680 --> 11:50.720
In fact, my lab had discovered that a brain region,

11:50.720 --> 11:53.240
right next to where that lime was located,

11:53.240 --> 11:57.480
was specifically involved in navigation.

11:57.480 --> 11:59.600
How could I not have put all this together,

11:59.600 --> 12:01.160
but I didn't until that moment?

12:01.160 --> 12:03.000
And I thought, of course.

12:03.000 --> 12:04.840
Of course, there's a thing in his brain,

12:04.840 --> 12:07.920
right next to the perihippocampal place area, which

12:07.920 --> 12:10.600
I discovered, and a nearby related region

12:10.600 --> 12:12.360
called retrospective spoolyneal cortex.

12:12.360 --> 12:13.400
Of course.

12:13.400 --> 12:16.160
And how the hell could I not have known?

12:16.160 --> 12:19.640
But I didn't know.

12:19.640 --> 12:23.760
In that earlier work, it had been nearly 20 years ago,

12:23.760 --> 12:26.280
I had a postdoc named Russell Epstein.

12:26.280 --> 12:28.440
And Russell was a computer vision guy,

12:28.440 --> 12:32.280
and he wanted to understand how we see by writing code

12:32.280 --> 12:34.520
to duplicate the algorithms that he thought

12:34.520 --> 12:38.040
go on in the human brain when we understand visual images.

12:38.040 --> 12:40.760
And that's a very respectable, cool line of work, which

12:40.760 --> 12:43.200
we'll learn a little bit about in here.

12:43.200 --> 12:45.320
And Russell was really a coding guy.

12:45.320 --> 12:48.680
At the time, we were just starting doing brain imaging.

12:48.680 --> 12:50.720
But Russell was like poo-pooing at all.

12:50.720 --> 12:52.000
It's like the flash in the pan.

12:52.000 --> 12:52.920
It's going to go by.

12:52.920 --> 12:53.760
It's trashy.

12:53.760 --> 12:55.920
So you guys get nice blobs on the brain.

12:55.920 --> 12:57.800
I'm not having any of it.

12:57.800 --> 13:01.040
And I kept saying, Russell, you need to get a job.

13:01.040 --> 13:03.880
Just do one experiment so you can show in your job talk

13:03.880 --> 13:05.200
that you can do brain imaging.

13:05.200 --> 13:06.520
It might help you.

13:06.520 --> 13:07.800
You don't need to do a lot of it.

13:07.800 --> 13:10.320
Just do one dumb experiment.

13:10.320 --> 13:13.080
Russell was interested in how we recognize scenes, not

13:13.080 --> 13:14.800
just objects and faces and words,

13:14.800 --> 13:16.200
but how do we know where we are?

13:16.200 --> 13:19.680
And how do we recognize if the scene is a city or a beach

13:19.680 --> 13:21.640
or whatever it is?

13:21.640 --> 13:24.240
I said, OK, Russell, we'll just scan people,

13:24.240 --> 13:26.280
looking at pictures of scenes, and looking

13:26.280 --> 13:28.000
at other kinds of pictures.

13:28.000 --> 13:29.560
And we'll just kind of see if there's

13:29.560 --> 13:32.280
any part of the brain that responds a lot to scenes.

13:32.280 --> 13:34.000
It really was not well thought out.

13:34.000 --> 13:35.960
This is not how you should do an experiment.

13:35.960 --> 13:39.440
It shouldn't be based on political calculations, lack

13:39.440 --> 13:41.080
of theory, any of the above.

13:41.080 --> 13:43.360
But the fact is, that's why we did that experiment.

13:43.360 --> 13:45.560
Russell needed to be able to show a brain image

13:45.560 --> 13:49.280
in his job talk, so we scanned some people looking at scenes.

13:49.280 --> 13:51.360
And the results knocked our socks off.

13:51.360 --> 13:54.480
We found a part of the brain that responds very selectively

13:54.480 --> 13:56.800
when you look at images of scenes,

13:56.800 --> 13:59.120
not when you look at faces, objects, words,

13:59.120 --> 14:01.400
or pretty much anything else.

14:01.400 --> 14:03.840
And so we'll learn more about that later in the course.

14:03.840 --> 14:06.280
We called it the Parahippocampal Place Area,

14:06.280 --> 14:09.240
and that launched a whole major line of work in my lab

14:09.240 --> 14:13.160
and now dozens of other labs around the world.

14:13.160 --> 14:15.720
So backtrack, we'd already found that region.

14:15.720 --> 14:18.440
And here's this lime in my friend Bob's brain

14:18.440 --> 14:21.440
sitting right next to the Parahippocampal Place Area.

14:28.160 --> 14:33.920
So then I remembered, let's look at the scans from my lab

14:33.920 --> 14:36.760
from a few years ago in Bob's brain.

14:36.760 --> 14:39.360
And so I fiddled around and found,

14:39.360 --> 14:42.400
managed to download the files.

14:42.400 --> 14:43.680
And there it was.

14:43.680 --> 14:46.000
You could see that same blob.

14:46.000 --> 14:49.000
But in the scans from a few years before, it was much smaller.

14:49.000 --> 14:52.160
It was the size of a grape.

14:52.160 --> 14:54.840
And so that told us a bunch of things.

14:54.840 --> 14:57.720
Most importantly, it told us this thing is growing really

14:57.720 --> 14:59.240
slowly.

14:59.240 --> 15:02.360
And that was hugely important because brain tumors

15:02.360 --> 15:05.960
are very bad news, and they usually grow really fast.

15:05.960 --> 15:08.200
And the fact that it grew really slowly

15:08.200 --> 15:12.240
told us that this was not one of the worst, most invasive,

15:12.240 --> 15:13.320
most horrible ones.

15:13.320 --> 15:14.920
It was clearly a problem.

15:14.920 --> 15:21.360
It was big, but at least it wasn't growing hugely fast.

15:21.360 --> 15:25.160
But how poignant that there it was in my own damn data,

15:25.160 --> 15:27.800
and I hadn't seen it in my friend's brain.

15:27.800 --> 15:30.320
Well, I'm not a radiologist.

15:30.320 --> 15:32.520
I'm a basic researcher, and I didn't look,

15:32.520 --> 15:35.040
and I didn't see it.

15:35.040 --> 15:38.840
So indeed, the next day, the docs told us

15:38.840 --> 15:41.880
that they thought this was meningioma, not cancer,

15:41.880 --> 15:44.000
who knew that you could have tumors that weren't cancer,

15:44.000 --> 15:45.720
but you can.

15:45.720 --> 15:48.040
And they still need to come out if they're big enough,

15:48.040 --> 15:49.640
and that's very serious, but it's not

15:49.640 --> 15:54.320
as bad as having a cancer in your brain.

15:54.320 --> 15:56.080
So as we're collecting information,

15:56.080 --> 15:59.040
the next day I'm hanging out in the hospital room,

15:59.040 --> 16:01.960
and there was an amusing moment when one of the residents

16:01.960 --> 16:03.560
came by, and he's taking the history

16:03.560 --> 16:05.120
and asking all the basic questions.

16:05.120 --> 16:07.040
And I said kind of sheepishly because you

16:07.040 --> 16:09.440
don't want to seem like you know more than the residents.

16:09.440 --> 16:10.920
And in fact, I didn't really know more,

16:10.920 --> 16:12.840
but I just thought I'd provide a little information.

16:12.840 --> 16:15.200
And I said, you know, he's actually

16:15.200 --> 16:16.800
had symptoms for a bunch of years,

16:16.800 --> 16:19.200
and there's a region of the brain nearby

16:19.200 --> 16:21.680
that I've actually studied a little bit.

16:21.680 --> 16:24.000
And the residents is like, we know who you are.

16:27.920 --> 16:33.560
So much for my trying to stay under the radar.

16:33.560 --> 16:36.320
That afternoon, I talked to a neurosurgeon friend of mine

16:36.320 --> 16:38.440
because I figured, OK, we need advice.

16:38.440 --> 16:39.640
We need help.

16:39.640 --> 16:45.680
And the neurosurgeon friend said, quote,

16:45.680 --> 16:47.440
it got branded in my brain.

16:47.440 --> 16:50.200
She said, it is of paramount importance

16:50.200 --> 16:52.520
that you find the best neurosurgeon.

16:52.520 --> 16:54.800
It's the difference between whether Bob

16:54.800 --> 16:59.000
dies on the table or goes on to live a normal life.

16:59.000 --> 17:00.880
So this is the privileged part of the story.

17:00.880 --> 17:03.600
I'm not that well connected, but I'm a little bit connected.

17:03.600 --> 17:06.280
And I kind of dug around and did what I could.

17:06.280 --> 17:08.920
And we spent a couple of weeks, and we

17:08.920 --> 17:12.760
found the best neurosurgeon.

17:12.760 --> 17:18.440
And the night before the surgery,

17:18.440 --> 17:20.880
Bob is staying over at my house because the surgery was

17:20.880 --> 17:22.520
in a Boston hospital.

17:22.520 --> 17:24.520
And I thought, you know, I've been dancing around this

17:24.520 --> 17:26.600
for years, but now, like, it's all out in the open.

17:26.600 --> 17:28.960
We know there's a problem, and I'm going to test him.

17:28.960 --> 17:31.640
I'm going to find out what the hell is going on.

17:31.640 --> 17:35.480
This is, after all, one of the basic forms of data

17:35.480 --> 17:36.880
that we collected in my field.

17:36.880 --> 17:39.720
That is testing people with problems in their brain

17:39.720 --> 17:41.960
to try to figure out what things they can do

17:41.960 --> 17:43.280
and what things they can't do.

17:43.280 --> 17:45.560
It's a way of figuring out what the basic components

17:45.560 --> 17:47.080
of the mind and brain are.

17:47.080 --> 17:49.840
It's actually the oldest, most venerable method in our field,

17:49.840 --> 17:52.640
and it's still a hugely important one.

17:52.640 --> 17:54.280
So I thought, what the hell?

17:54.280 --> 17:57.600
So I said, OK, Bob, draw me a sketch map of the floor

17:57.600 --> 18:00.080
plan of your house.

18:00.080 --> 18:03.200
And so Bob takes a few minutes, and he draws this thing.

18:03.200 --> 18:05.640
And it was shocking.

18:05.640 --> 18:10.240
There weren't even the rooms in a rectilinearly arranged house.

18:10.240 --> 18:12.520
They weren't even aligned.

18:12.520 --> 18:14.240
There was like a soup of lines.

18:14.240 --> 18:17.600
There was no organization from one room to the next.

18:17.600 --> 18:21.040
And Bob kind of realized this kind of isn't right, is it?

18:21.040 --> 18:22.720
But he didn't know how to fix it.

18:22.720 --> 18:25.480
And he said he just couldn't visualize what it looked like

18:25.480 --> 18:29.680
to be in his house, and so he couldn't draw the floor plan.

18:29.680 --> 18:32.120
And I thought, OK, he hasn't been there in a couple of days.

18:32.120 --> 18:34.320
I gave him another piece of paper, and I said, OK,

18:34.320 --> 18:40.000
draw the floor plan of my house, where you are right now.

18:40.000 --> 18:45.800
And so Bob took a couple minutes and delivered a similar mess.

18:45.800 --> 18:49.680
He couldn't even imagine the layout of the room next to him

18:49.680 --> 18:54.280
that he'd been at, been in a few minutes before.

18:54.280 --> 18:57.280
And then, trying to channel my inner neuropsychologist,

18:57.280 --> 19:00.280
I thought, OK, gave him another piece of paper.

19:00.280 --> 19:03.800
And I said, OK, Bob, draw a bicycle.

19:03.800 --> 19:04.880
Why did I choose a bicycle?

19:04.880 --> 19:06.520
Because it's a multi-part object that

19:06.520 --> 19:08.120
has a bunch of different bits that

19:08.120 --> 19:10.400
have a particular relationship to each other,

19:10.400 --> 19:13.240
just as the rooms in a house have a particular spatial

19:13.240 --> 19:14.680
relationship to each other.

19:14.680 --> 19:17.160
And I wanted to know, is his problem specifically

19:17.160 --> 19:21.640
about places, or is it about any complex multi-part thing

19:21.640 --> 19:25.040
that you have to remember the relationships to?

19:25.040 --> 19:27.520
Bob is no artist, to put it mildly,

19:27.520 --> 19:30.640
but his bicycle was clearly recognizable as a bicycle.

19:30.640 --> 19:32.840
It had the two wheels and the right relationship,

19:32.840 --> 19:35.880
and it had all the basic parts in roughly the same,

19:35.880 --> 19:37.520
the right place.

19:37.520 --> 19:40.840
I then had him draw a lobster, another multi-part object,

19:40.840 --> 19:42.840
and also his lobster was not beautiful,

19:42.840 --> 19:46.040
but had everything in the right place.

19:46.040 --> 19:47.600
And so that's very telling.

19:47.600 --> 19:51.360
He had a specific problem in, I don't know, imagining,

19:51.360 --> 19:52.680
reproducing, remembering.

19:52.680 --> 19:54.480
It's not totally clear.

19:54.480 --> 19:56.640
The arrangements of parts in a room,

19:56.640 --> 20:00.680
but not the arrangements of parts in an object.

20:00.680 --> 20:02.720
We'll get back to that more in a few weeks.

20:06.720 --> 20:11.640
So what do I want to say here?

20:11.640 --> 20:13.840
Is that all that?

20:13.840 --> 20:18.040
So the next day, Bob has an 11-hour surgery,

20:18.040 --> 20:21.680
major hardcore extreme neurosurgery.

20:21.680 --> 20:25.040
Remove a huge piece of bone from the back of your head,

20:25.040 --> 20:27.480
pull apart the hemispheres of the brain like this,

20:27.480 --> 20:34.160
go in multiple inches, and remove a lime, like holy crap.

20:34.160 --> 20:38.080
Said lime was right near the vein of Galen.

20:38.080 --> 20:40.720
Galen lived, what, a couple thousand years ago.

20:40.720 --> 20:42.360
The fact that there's a vein of Galen

20:42.360 --> 20:45.680
means it's a big-ass vein, the kind of vein that even Galen

20:45.680 --> 20:49.920
would have found with dissection 2,000 years ago.

20:49.920 --> 20:52.680
This lime was all wrapped around and interleaved

20:52.680 --> 20:54.000
with the vein of Galen.

20:54.000 --> 20:55.400
Not good.

20:55.400 --> 20:58.520
But because we found the best neurosurgeon,

20:58.520 --> 21:01.560
and because we have extreme privilege,

21:01.560 --> 21:05.040
and all the possible medical resources and expertise

21:05.040 --> 21:08.880
you could possibly hope for, Bob sailed through the surgery.

21:08.880 --> 21:11.680
And an hour after the surgery, I'm chatting with him,

21:11.680 --> 21:13.080
and he's making sense.

21:13.080 --> 21:16.240
Amazing, right?

21:16.240 --> 21:22.160
So literally, two days later, they sent him home.

21:22.160 --> 21:25.880
And a few days after that, he's back at work, no problem.

21:25.880 --> 21:27.960
Totally fine.

21:27.960 --> 21:31.760
But now we get to the question you're probably thinking about.

21:31.760 --> 21:34.880
What about his navigational abilities?

21:34.880 --> 21:38.360
The sad answer is, nothing doing.

21:38.360 --> 21:41.880
None of it came back at all.

21:41.880 --> 21:43.880
Thank God for iPhones.

21:43.880 --> 21:47.040
If Bob lived 30 years ago, he wouldn't be able to function.

21:47.040 --> 21:53.560
But he goes everywhere using his iPhone GPS, everywhere.

21:53.560 --> 21:56.680
And this fact that he didn't recover his navigational

21:56.680 --> 22:00.200
abilities is consistent with the whole literature that

22:00.200 --> 22:02.840
we'll consider later in the course.

22:02.840 --> 22:05.680
That often, not always, but often,

22:05.680 --> 22:08.040
if you have brain damage, especially

22:08.040 --> 22:09.960
to some of these very specialized circuits

22:09.960 --> 22:13.520
that we'll talk about, you don't recover later.

22:13.520 --> 22:16.160
If the damage is early, you may well recover.

22:16.200 --> 22:18.160
Children have much more plastic brains

22:18.160 --> 22:20.120
that can adjust after brain damage.

22:20.120 --> 22:21.720
Adults, not so good.

22:25.560 --> 22:28.720
So Bob's doing fine.

22:28.720 --> 22:30.560
That's my story.

22:30.560 --> 22:33.120
Any thoughts or questions?

22:33.120 --> 22:34.120
Yeah?

22:34.120 --> 22:36.640
He can tell the difference from the right to the left,

22:36.640 --> 22:37.640
not on the left.

22:37.640 --> 22:38.880
Yes.

22:38.880 --> 22:40.200
Yes.

22:40.200 --> 22:41.840
And it's very interesting.

22:41.840 --> 22:43.840
There are many of his spatial abilities,

22:43.880 --> 22:46.200
that are absolutely intact.

22:46.200 --> 22:50.600
And yet, the ones related to navigation are not.

22:50.600 --> 22:51.600
Yeah?

22:51.600 --> 22:52.600
Yeah.

22:52.600 --> 22:53.600
Yeah.

22:53.600 --> 22:54.600
No problem.

22:54.600 --> 22:57.600
But he's always looking at his damn phone to get directions

22:57.600 --> 23:03.200
or to listen to the GPS directions system.

23:03.200 --> 23:04.200
So driving is no problem.

23:04.200 --> 23:05.400
It's another kind of left-right.

23:05.400 --> 23:07.920
The immediate spatial orientation abilities

23:07.920 --> 23:09.280
are absolutely fine.

23:09.280 --> 23:11.600
But knowing where am I now, I don't know.

23:11.600 --> 23:12.360
Fine.

23:12.360 --> 23:16.280
But knowing where am I now and how would I get there from here

23:16.280 --> 23:18.920
is blitzed.

23:18.920 --> 23:19.520
Other questions?

23:19.520 --> 23:20.520
Yeah?

23:20.520 --> 23:22.520
Can you recognize what familiar is?

23:22.520 --> 23:24.200
Great question.

23:24.200 --> 23:24.840
Yes.

23:24.840 --> 23:27.080
He can recognize familiar places.

23:27.080 --> 23:30.040
What he can't do is he can say, oh, right.

23:30.040 --> 23:31.240
That's the front of our house.

23:31.240 --> 23:37.040
Or that's such and such cafe that's near our house.

23:37.040 --> 23:39.120
What he can't do is say, which way would you

23:39.120 --> 23:40.840
turn from there to go home?

23:45.840 --> 23:47.120
Great question.

23:47.120 --> 23:47.960
Great question.

23:47.960 --> 23:49.680
A little bit.

23:49.680 --> 23:52.240
So he can navigate a little bit with his GPS.

23:52.240 --> 23:54.120
And because he's learned certain routes

23:54.120 --> 23:57.000
as a series of almost verbal commands,

23:57.000 --> 23:59.120
like if you're here, turn right, then do, do, do, do,

23:59.120 --> 24:00.760
like that whole kind of thing.

24:00.760 --> 24:03.000
It's not what any of you guys could do.

24:03.000 --> 24:05.760
If you guys are driving around in Cambridge

24:05.760 --> 24:07.960
or walking around campus, remember

24:07.960 --> 24:10.640
where they blocked off this whole middle of campus

24:10.640 --> 24:11.760
a couple of years ago?

24:11.760 --> 24:12.880
It was so irritating.

24:12.880 --> 24:14.200
I would go there and it's like, oh, god.

24:14.200 --> 24:15.080
They blocked it off.

24:15.080 --> 24:17.440
I can't get over to lobby 7.

24:17.440 --> 24:19.440
Well, you immediately come up with an alternate route.

24:19.440 --> 24:21.240
It's like, OK, I guess we're going to have to do this.

24:21.240 --> 24:22.640
You come up with an alternate route.

24:22.640 --> 24:25.560
This is what a normal navigation system can do.

24:25.560 --> 24:26.800
Bob can't do that at all.

24:26.800 --> 24:28.840
He's like, route blocked?

24:28.840 --> 24:29.520
No idea.

24:29.520 --> 24:32.800
Get out the phone, right?

24:32.800 --> 24:33.300
Yeah?

24:33.300 --> 24:35.580
Does he get at estimating distances?

24:35.580 --> 24:38.940
Does he know something is a certain number of miles away?

24:38.940 --> 24:40.740
Yes.

24:40.740 --> 24:41.980
Yes, he is.

24:41.980 --> 24:44.380
And that's very interesting.

24:44.380 --> 24:46.460
But that seems to be kind of a different thing.

24:46.460 --> 24:48.420
You could think about all the different kinds of cues

24:48.420 --> 24:53.020
you have for distance beyond your kind of literal navigation

24:53.020 --> 24:55.020
skills.

24:55.020 --> 24:56.020
Yeah?

24:56.020 --> 25:00.380
Can you retrace the steps a couple of minutes after?

25:00.380 --> 25:01.660
A little bit.

25:01.700 --> 25:03.700
A couple minutes, yes.

25:03.700 --> 25:06.820
The next day, I mean, it would be kind of like this thing.

25:06.820 --> 25:09.460
It's like, you know, I vaguely remember that I was here.

25:09.460 --> 25:11.820
I turned right, so I better do that again.

25:11.820 --> 25:13.340
Yeah, did you have a question?

25:13.340 --> 25:17.100
Can you navigate within buildings?

25:17.100 --> 25:18.500
No, not very well.

25:18.500 --> 25:21.580
And this is a problem, because iPhones don't usually.

25:21.580 --> 25:25.460
So new hotels, big problem.

25:25.460 --> 25:28.180
Finding the bathroom down the hall or the front door

25:28.180 --> 25:31.300
in a hotel, big problem.

25:31.300 --> 25:34.580
Yeah, I mean, you know, these are problems you can come up

25:34.580 --> 25:37.340
with workarounds, but it's not life-threatening.

25:37.340 --> 25:40.100
But it's extremely inconvenient.

25:40.100 --> 25:41.020
Yeah?

25:41.020 --> 25:44.900
So this is the case that those navigational skills

25:44.900 --> 25:47.860
that he developed longer, a long time ago,

25:47.860 --> 25:48.660
those are stronger.

25:48.660 --> 25:51.580
So he has a harder time developing.

25:51.580 --> 25:53.300
Sorry, I mean, so new hotels are a problem,

25:53.300 --> 25:56.500
but if it's a fixie, it's more familiar like his home.

25:56.500 --> 25:57.900
Is it easier for him to navigate?

25:57.900 --> 25:58.900
It's a great question.

25:58.900 --> 26:02.340
You might think that the kind of navigational maps

26:02.340 --> 26:04.260
you laid down long ago would be intact.

26:04.260 --> 26:07.380
So is it just that you can't learn new ones?

26:07.380 --> 26:10.060
So it's a great question.

26:10.060 --> 26:12.620
The answer is kind of complicated in this case.

26:12.620 --> 26:16.020
For routes that he's memorized, there's

26:16.020 --> 26:18.060
a whole different system for knowing a route

26:18.060 --> 26:21.420
and really having an abstract knowledge of a place that

26:21.420 --> 26:23.380
enables you to devise a new route if something

26:23.380 --> 26:24.620
is blocked on that route.

26:24.620 --> 26:27.660
So for highly over-learned routes, he's OK.

26:27.660 --> 26:29.420
Like he remembers, like this you do.

26:29.420 --> 26:30.220
It's like a sequence.

26:30.220 --> 26:32.460
It's like a memorized motor sequence.

26:32.460 --> 26:34.780
You do A, and then B, and then C, and then D.

26:34.780 --> 26:37.900
So he's OK with those with routes he learned long ago.

26:37.900 --> 26:42.500
But he is not good at coming up with a new route in a place

26:42.500 --> 26:45.900
that he learned long ago.

26:45.900 --> 26:46.300
All right.

26:46.300 --> 26:47.340
We'll take one last question.

26:47.340 --> 26:48.340
Yeah?

26:49.020 --> 26:51.820
Does he have conscious access to past knowledge

26:51.820 --> 26:55.620
that he can't use in the case?

26:55.620 --> 26:58.660
And does he have conscious knowledge that this is the case?

26:58.660 --> 27:00.620
Can he, how does he specify that?

27:00.620 --> 27:03.780
Oh, I'm having trouble figuring this out.

27:03.780 --> 27:04.900
No, he knows.

27:04.900 --> 27:06.820
Well, he knows, because when he tries to figure out

27:06.820 --> 27:08.580
which way to head, he has no idea.

27:08.580 --> 27:12.460
So he's extremely aware of it and very articulate

27:12.460 --> 27:14.060
on precisely what happens.

27:14.060 --> 27:18.300
And so what he says is, like, if he's looking at a place,

27:18.660 --> 27:19.660
here's something he says.

27:19.660 --> 27:20.860
He's looking at a place.

27:20.860 --> 27:22.260
He knows where he is, because there's

27:22.260 --> 27:23.820
all kinds of other bits of information

27:23.820 --> 27:25.940
that tell you where you are, because you intended to go there

27:25.940 --> 27:27.580
and the relevant things are happening and all this.

27:27.580 --> 27:31.220
He knows where he is, and it looks familiar.

27:31.220 --> 27:35.340
If he tries to imagine what's behind him,

27:35.340 --> 27:37.420
he says that he, like, starts to get it,

27:37.420 --> 27:39.180
and it just kind of vaporizes.

27:39.180 --> 27:40.620
He just can't hang on to it.

27:40.620 --> 27:44.420
He can't kind of construct a stable mental image

27:44.420 --> 27:46.500
of nearby places.

27:46.500 --> 27:48.060
So I don't know exactly what that means,

27:48.060 --> 27:50.620
but he's very articulate and can report

27:50.620 --> 27:53.140
what he experiences when he tries

27:53.140 --> 27:55.100
to access this kind of information.

27:56.380 --> 27:58.620
So what you guys, we'll go on, but what I want to say

27:58.620 --> 28:02.540
is what you guys just did is exactly what we do in my field.

28:02.540 --> 28:05.820
We try to take a mental ability and tease it apart

28:05.820 --> 28:08.260
and say, is it exactly this or is it exactly that?

28:08.260 --> 28:11.740
And you guys all just did it beautifully, right?

28:11.740 --> 28:14.620
So a lot of what we do in my field is kind of,

28:14.660 --> 28:18.660
this kind of common sense parsing of mental abilities.

28:18.660 --> 28:21.500
What is a particular mental ability?

28:21.500 --> 28:23.100
How does it relate to some other one?

28:23.100 --> 28:24.300
Are these things separable?

28:24.300 --> 28:26.220
Can you lose one and not the other?

28:26.220 --> 28:29.100
Do they live in different parts of the brain, et cetera?

28:30.260 --> 28:32.260
All right, so that's the story.

28:33.100 --> 28:38.100
I'm gonna cash out some of the particular themes

28:39.580 --> 28:41.540
that came out from this story

28:41.540 --> 28:43.540
that we'll echo through this course.

28:43.540 --> 28:45.060
And the first and most obvious one

28:45.060 --> 28:48.460
is the brain isn't just a big bunch of mush, right?

28:48.460 --> 28:51.460
It has structure, it has organization.

28:51.460 --> 28:54.020
The different bits do different things, okay?

28:55.820 --> 28:59.060
Importantly, when Bob had this big lime in his head,

28:59.060 --> 29:01.540
he didn't just get a little bit stupid.

29:01.540 --> 29:05.180
No, his IQ, if he'd take an IQ test, would be unchanged.

29:05.180 --> 29:08.360
He lost a very specific mental ability, okay?

29:09.340 --> 29:12.020
And that is fascinating,

29:12.020 --> 29:13.860
but it's also good news for science

29:13.860 --> 29:15.500
because often when you try to understand

29:15.500 --> 29:18.100
a complicated thing, a great way to make progress

29:18.100 --> 29:20.220
is to first figure out what the parts are

29:20.220 --> 29:21.540
and then later try to figure out

29:21.540 --> 29:23.160
how does each individual part work

29:23.160 --> 29:24.660
and how do they work together?

29:24.660 --> 29:25.900
But if there's part structure,

29:25.900 --> 29:28.140
there's at least a place to start, okay?

29:29.300 --> 29:33.860
Okay, second theme is that some parts of the brain

29:33.860 --> 29:36.860
do extremely specific things, right?

29:36.860 --> 29:39.180
Not all of them, some of them are quite general

29:39.180 --> 29:41.720
and are engaged in lots of different mental processes,

29:41.720 --> 29:43.760
but some are remarkably specific.

29:43.760 --> 29:45.200
We'll talk a lot about that.

29:46.400 --> 29:50.160
Third big theme, the organization of the brain

29:50.160 --> 29:53.520
echoes the architecture of the mind, okay?

29:55.640 --> 29:58.120
And I would say the fundamental pieces of the brain

29:58.120 --> 30:01.640
are telling us what are fundamental parts of the mind.

30:01.640 --> 30:03.120
And that's why I'm in this field.

30:03.120 --> 30:04.360
That's what I think is cool.

30:04.360 --> 30:06.040
You know, the brain is just like a bunch of cells,

30:06.040 --> 30:07.080
like it's a physical thing.

30:07.080 --> 30:08.740
Who cares about a physical thing?

30:08.740 --> 30:11.780
The reason we care about it is that's where our mind lives.

30:11.780 --> 30:13.140
And if we study that physical thing,

30:13.140 --> 30:15.500
we can learn something about our minds.

30:15.500 --> 30:18.180
And that's pretty cosmic, I think.

30:18.180 --> 30:20.740
So the point of all of this kind of work is not to say,

30:20.740 --> 30:23.380
oh, that mental process is here, not there.

30:23.380 --> 30:24.220
Who cares?

30:24.220 --> 30:25.060
I don't really care.

30:25.060 --> 30:26.980
I mean, at some point you need to have a ballpark sense.

30:26.980 --> 30:28.780
You need to know to study the things.

30:28.780 --> 30:31.620
But the interesting question is not where these things

30:31.620 --> 30:34.060
are in the brain, but which mental processes

30:34.060 --> 30:37.380
have their own specialized machinery and why those?

30:37.700 --> 30:40.020
Yeah.

30:40.020 --> 30:43.460
Another important theme, how do brains change?

30:43.460 --> 30:45.260
Bob didn't recover after his brain

30:45.260 --> 30:47.740
damaged in that very particular mental function

30:47.740 --> 30:49.580
that he lost.

30:49.580 --> 30:52.500
If all of that had happened when he was five years old,

30:52.500 --> 30:54.980
he probably would have.

30:54.980 --> 30:58.180
So how do brains change over normal development?

30:58.180 --> 31:01.140
How do they change from learning and experience?

31:01.140 --> 31:03.780
How do they change after injury?

31:03.780 --> 31:06.980
And the final theme echoed in that story

31:06.980 --> 31:08.700
is there are lots and lots of different ways

31:08.700 --> 31:10.820
to study the brain.

31:10.820 --> 31:12.980
There are the simple behavioral observations.

31:12.980 --> 31:15.300
Bob can't navigate, but he can do everything else.

31:15.300 --> 31:17.100
OK, that's really deep and informative.

31:17.100 --> 31:20.980
Low-tech, but really powerful.

31:20.980 --> 31:24.340
The anatomical brain images that showed where the line was

31:24.340 --> 31:27.300
in Bob's brain, that gives you another kind of information

31:27.300 --> 31:30.340
where's the physical structure of the brain.

31:30.340 --> 31:33.020
The functional images that we had done in my lab

31:33.020 --> 31:36.780
to discover the parahippocampal place area.

31:36.780 --> 31:40.020
And the studies of what mental abilities are preserved

31:40.020 --> 31:42.460
in which are lost and people who have alterations

31:42.460 --> 31:44.020
of their brain.

31:44.020 --> 31:47.180
So those are just a few of the kinds of methods in our field,

31:47.180 --> 31:50.620
each of which tells us about a different kind of thing

31:50.620 --> 31:52.540
about the brain.

31:52.540 --> 31:56.580
So those are the themes I was trying to get at here.

