by my postdoc, Katherine Dobbs.

38:33.100 --> 38:36.420
And we'll hear more about that.

38:36.420 --> 38:38.700
But let's first step back a second and say, OK,

38:38.700 --> 38:40.660
do they really perform as well as humans,

38:40.660 --> 38:43.700
even on just object recognition?

38:43.700 --> 38:48.180
Well, what if we tested it on images, not in ImageNet?

38:48.220 --> 38:50.180
ImageNet is a pretty good test, because these things,

38:50.180 --> 38:51.900
as you can see, are highly variable.

38:51.900 --> 38:52.820
They have backgrounds.

38:52.820 --> 38:53.580
They're complicated.

38:53.580 --> 38:55.300
They're real-world images.

38:55.300 --> 38:59.500
But they were photographs taken by people in a particular way

38:59.500 --> 39:01.780
with a particular goal.

39:01.780 --> 39:03.780
And most of the photographs you take, you throw out,

39:03.780 --> 39:05.500
they don't end up in ImageNet.

39:05.500 --> 39:08.940
ImageNet is a weird little idiosyncratic subset

39:08.940 --> 39:11.380
of the kind of visual experience that we have.

39:11.380 --> 39:14.260
So would this really generalize?

39:14.260 --> 39:17.100
So it so happens that Boris Katz and Andrei

39:17.100 --> 39:19.380
Marbu across the street in Seasale

39:19.380 --> 39:21.180
