39:51.540 --> 39:53.860
or move it here and send us the images.

39:53.860 --> 39:57.340
So they are getting, I think, hundreds of thousands of images

39:57.340 --> 39:58.740
to test this on.

39:58.740 --> 40:00.700
And they're much more variable in the location

40:00.700 --> 40:04.220
of the object in the image and its orientation and so forth.

40:04.220 --> 40:06.500
So for example, you guys have no problem

40:06.500 --> 40:07.820
telling what that thing is, but it's

40:07.820 --> 40:10.340
a slightly atypical example.

40:10.340 --> 40:12.580
Likewise, what's the object on the floor there?

40:12.580 --> 40:14.260
You can tell what it is, but it's

40:14.300 --> 40:16.540
slightly atypical example.

40:16.540 --> 40:20.500
And so what Boris and Andre are finding

40:20.500 --> 40:22.380
is that human performance is still pretty good

40:22.380 --> 40:24.100
on these images.

40:24.100 --> 40:27.900
But the deep nets are terrible at this stuff.

40:27.900 --> 40:31.940
So ResNet, one of the more recent ones,

40:31.940 --> 40:34.460
drops from 71% correct on ImageNet

40:34.460 --> 40:38.220
to around 25% correct on these images.

40:38.220 --> 40:41.980
And the other similar, fancy, more recent networks

40:41.980 --> 40:43.860
