You need to know that he can't see that Obama's doing it.

44:43.900 --> 44:46.740
You need to know that they can see it, even though he can't.

44:46.740 --> 44:49.020
And that's kind of the essence of humor.

44:49.020 --> 44:52.980
There's just a whole universe of rich structural information

44:52.980 --> 44:55.140
going in here that is part of what it means

44:55.140 --> 44:57.300
to understand this picture.

44:57.300 --> 45:02.740
And no deep net is even close to doing that kind of thing.

45:02.740 --> 45:04.420
OK?

45:04.420 --> 45:08.740
So bottom line of all this is, or let me just go on more

45:08.740 --> 45:14.340
generally, AI systems can't navigate new situations,

45:14.340 --> 45:19.020
infer what others believe, use language to communicate,

45:19.020 --> 45:22.740
write poetry and music to express how they feel,

45:22.740 --> 45:26.780
or create math to build bridges, devices,

45:26.780 --> 45:29.020
and lifesaving medicines.

45:29.020 --> 45:31.300
That's a quote from our leader, Jim DeCarlo,

45:31.300 --> 45:34.020
head of this department, published and wired a year ago

45:34.020 --> 45:37.780
in a beautiful article on the limitations of deep nets.

45:37.780 --> 45:41.540
But more generally, the point is that, yes, AI is taking

45:41.540 --> 45:43.780
a massive leap now when we're right in the middle of it,

45:43.780 --> 45:46.380
and it's super exciting, and it's helpful to neuroscience

45:46.380 --> 45:48.700
and cognitive science.

45:48.700 --> 45:51.700
But AI has a lot to learn from us, too.

45:51.700 --> 45:53.340
A lot to learn from what's going on in here

45:53.340 --> 45:56.460
and how this thing works that those AI systems still

45:56.460 --> 45:58.220
can't touch.

45:58.220 --> 45:58.940
OK.

45:58.940 --> 46:01.340
So all of that was my third reason for studying.

46:01.340 --> 46:04.020
We're still in the Y. Are we studying the human brain?

46:04.020 --> 46:05.980
The fourth reason to study the human brain

46:05.980 --> 46:08.140
is the one most compelling to me,

46:08.140 --> 46:11.820
and that is that it is just simply the greatest intellectual

46:11.820 --> 46:14.220
quest of all time.

46:14.220 --> 46:16.300
We could fight about cosmology.

46:16.300 --> 46:18.340
I'm not going to fight with you about anything else.

46:18.340 --> 46:20.020
I don't think there's any contest.

46:20.020 --> 46:22.700
It's the greatest intellectual quest of all time.

46:22.700 --> 46:24.700
And that's why I'm in it, and that's why I hope

46:24.700 --> 46:27.020
it'll be fun for you.

46:27.020 --> 46:29.820
OK, that was the Y. How are we going

46:29.820 --> 46:31.660
to study the human brain?

46:31.660 --> 46:33.060
So here's this thing.

46:33.060 --> 46:34.740
How are we going to figure out how it works?

46:34.740 --> 46:36.020
It's kind of daunting.

46:36.020 --> 46:38.060
It's not totally obvious.

46:38.060 --> 46:39.580
The first thing to realize is that there

46:39.580 --> 46:42.420
are lots of levels of organization in this thing,

46:42.420 --> 46:44.620
and hence, lots of ways of studying it.

46:44.620 --> 46:47.100
We could look at molecules and their interactions,

46:47.100 --> 46:49.340
lots of people in this building do that.

46:49.340 --> 46:52.460
We could look at properties of individual neurons.

46:52.460 --> 46:54.780
We could look at circuits of neurons interacting

46:54.780 --> 46:56.500
with each other.

46:56.500 --> 46:58.620
We could look at entire brain regions

46:58.620 --> 47:00.340
and what their functions are.

47:00.340 --> 47:03.060
We could look at networks of multiple brain regions

47:03.060 --> 47:05.700
interacting with each other.

47:05.700 --> 47:08.980
And so all of those things are possible.

47:08.980 --> 47:10.860
But actually, what we're going to do in the course

47:10.860 --> 47:13.060
is none of those things in particular.

47:13.060 --> 47:15.860
Instead, we're going to ask a somewhat different question.

47:15.860 --> 47:20.340
And that question is, how does the brain give rise to the mind?

47:20.340 --> 47:22.420
And to understand that question, we're

47:22.420 --> 47:25.380
going to do more at this level and less at the upper levels.

47:25.900 --> 47:28.220
OK?

47:28.220 --> 47:30.980
So to answer this question, we need to start with the mind.

47:30.980 --> 47:32.380
We need to, if we're going to understand,

47:32.380 --> 47:34.420
how does this thing produce a mind,

47:34.420 --> 47:36.300
we need to first figure out, what is a mind?

47:36.300 --> 47:38.500
What do we know about minds?

47:38.500 --> 47:40.620
OK?

47:40.620 --> 47:43.140
And so we need to start with the various mental functions

47:43.140 --> 47:46.460
that minds carry out, things like perception, vision,

47:46.460 --> 47:50.900
hearing, aspects of cognition, like understanding language,

47:50.900 --> 47:54.580
thinking about people, thinking about things, et cetera.

47:54.580 --> 47:55.820
OK?

47:55.820 --> 47:59.740
And so for each mental function, what we're going to do in here

47:59.740 --> 48:03.060
is start by trying to understand how it works in minds,

48:03.060 --> 48:05.180
as well as we can, or what it is that we're

48:05.180 --> 48:07.460
trying to understand that minds can do.

48:07.460 --> 48:09.260
What is computed and how?

48:09.260 --> 48:11.220
And then we're going to look at its brain basis

48:11.220 --> 48:12.660
and try to figure out what we can

48:12.660 --> 48:15.140
figure out about how that mental function is implemented

48:15.140 --> 48:16.380
in a brain.

48:16.380 --> 48:19.140
So the first question we'll ask for all of these domains

48:19.140 --> 48:22.820
is, is there specialized machinery to do that thing?

48:22.820 --> 48:24.380
And then we'll ask, what information

48:24.380 --> 48:27.140
is represented in the relevant parts of the brain?

48:27.140 --> 48:30.060
And when is that information represented?

48:30.060 --> 48:31.220
OK?

48:31.220 --> 48:32.780
And how?

48:32.780 --> 48:35.500
OK, so how are we going to answer those questions?

48:35.500 --> 48:38.060
Well, there's lots and lots of methods in our field.

48:38.060 --> 48:38.860
OK?

48:38.860 --> 48:42.140
And so the first set of methods, if we want to understand minds,

48:42.140 --> 48:44.740
the first set of methods are the basic stuff

48:44.740 --> 48:46.900
of cognitive science, psychophysics.

48:46.900 --> 48:49.580
That means showing people visual stimuli

48:49.580 --> 48:52.420
or playing them sounds and asking them what they see or hear.

48:52.420 --> 48:55.700
Nice and low-tech, but lots has been learned from those methods.

48:55.700 --> 48:57.740
You collect reaction time and accuracy,

48:57.740 --> 48:59.660
and it's amazing how much you can learn

48:59.660 --> 49:03.620
from these methods that have been around for 100 years or more.

49:03.620 --> 49:06.580
Perceptual illusions are similarly very informative

49:06.580 --> 49:08.300
about how minds work.

49:08.300 --> 49:12.260
Now, let me say an important thing that arises here.

49:12.260 --> 49:14.220
Last year was the first time I taught this course,

49:14.220 --> 49:15.780
and I would say it went so-so.

49:15.780 --> 49:18.580
I'm aiming for it to be much better this year.

49:18.580 --> 49:20.100
And one of the ways I'm trying to do that

49:20.100 --> 49:23.700
is to be responsive to the student evals I got last year,

49:23.700 --> 49:26.100
which were not fabulous across the board,

49:26.100 --> 49:27.380
hurt my feelings badly.

49:27.380 --> 49:30.180
But once I got over myself, I decided to just listen to them

49:30.180 --> 49:31.540
and try to fix it.

49:31.540 --> 49:34.300
And one way to fix it is to be honest with you today about what

49:34.300 --> 49:35.980
this course is going to cover.

49:35.980 --> 49:43.060
So in my evals, student 50458, bless them, offered this comment.

49:43.060 --> 49:45.180
This class was not sold in the correct way.

49:45.180 --> 49:46.660
It should not be called the human brain,

49:46.660 --> 49:49.020
because it was basically just a cognitive science not a brain

49:49.020 --> 49:49.520
class.

49:49.520 --> 49:52.480
I expected to learn very different material.

49:52.480 --> 49:54.040
So I don't know who the student is.

49:54.040 --> 49:58.120
I wish I could apologize to them, but I will say to you,

49:58.120 --> 50:02.720
sorry, student 50458, sorry to make that clear.

50:02.720 --> 50:04.920
The fundamental reason the brain is cool

50:04.920 --> 50:07.240
is that it gives rise to the mind.

50:07.240 --> 50:10.280
And that means that studying the biological properties

50:10.280 --> 50:12.680
of the brain without considering the mental functions

50:12.680 --> 50:15.440
it implements, it'd be kind of like trying

50:15.440 --> 50:17.320
to study the physical properties of a book

50:17.320 --> 50:20.480
without considering the meaning of its text.

50:20.480 --> 50:22.240
So we're going to spend a lot of time

50:22.240 --> 50:23.920
doing cognitive science in here.

50:23.920 --> 50:27.080
And if you had a different impression, sorry about that,

50:27.080 --> 50:29.040
but that's what we're doing here.

50:29.040 --> 50:30.040
OK?

50:30.040 --> 50:30.720
All right.

50:30.720 --> 50:32.160
So how are we going to answer this up?

50:32.160 --> 50:34.280
Lots of cognitive science.

50:34.280 --> 50:37.120
So how are we going to look at the brain basis?

50:37.120 --> 50:39.320
Well, we're going to look at neuropsychology patients,

50:39.320 --> 50:41.360
people like Bob, who have damage to the brain

50:41.360 --> 50:43.960
and what functions get preserved and lost.

50:43.960 --> 50:47.160
We'll look at a lot of studies with functional MRI,

50:47.200 --> 50:49.120
neurophysiology, where you can record

50:49.120 --> 50:52.040
from individual neurons in animal brains

50:52.040 --> 50:55.320
and in rare cases, even in human brains,

50:55.320 --> 50:56.920
under clinical situations where they

50:56.920 --> 51:00.720
need to have electrodes in their brain anyway for neurosurgery.

51:00.720 --> 51:05.800
We'll look at EEG, recorded from electrodes on the scalp.

51:05.800 --> 51:08.280
And MEG, recording from magnetic fields,

51:08.280 --> 51:11.360
from squids placed next to the scalp.

51:11.360 --> 51:13.160
We'll look at connectivity measures

51:13.160 --> 51:16.720
with a method called diffusion tractography, et cetera.

51:16.720 --> 51:18.760
So lots of methods.

51:18.760 --> 51:21.920
And so which mental functions will we cover?

51:21.920 --> 51:23.680
Well, to tell you about that, I need

51:23.680 --> 51:25.880
to tell you about the huge progress that

51:25.880 --> 51:28.480
has happened in our field in the last 20 years.

51:28.480 --> 51:28.880
OK?

51:28.880 --> 51:31.320
All of this is quite recent.

51:31.320 --> 51:34.640
And so let's back up to 1990.

51:34.640 --> 51:36.440
Here is approximately what we knew

51:36.440 --> 51:39.800
about the organization of the human brain in 1990.

51:39.800 --> 51:41.840
The black ovals are the bits that

51:41.840 --> 51:44.160
are primary sensory and motor regions

51:44.160 --> 51:47.800
that have been known for a long time, even by 1990.

51:47.800 --> 51:49.160
And the colored bits are the bits

51:49.160 --> 51:52.280
where we had some idea that face recognition might go on

51:52.280 --> 51:55.480
somewhere in the back end of the bottom of the right hemisphere

51:55.480 --> 51:58.160
because of people who had damage back there and lost

51:58.160 --> 52:01.760
their face recognition ability, sometimes preserving

52:01.760 --> 52:05.440
their ability to visually recognize words and scenes

52:05.440 --> 52:08.760
and objects, only losing their ability to recognize faces.

52:08.760 --> 52:10.080
OK?

52:10.080 --> 52:13.360
The language regions we had known about for nearly 200 years

52:13.360 --> 52:15.280
were Broca and Wernicke and others

52:15.280 --> 52:17.880
who had studied patients with damage in those regions

52:17.880 --> 52:20.920
and noted that they had problems with language function.

52:20.920 --> 52:22.920
And similarly, many people had reported

52:22.920 --> 52:25.640
that if you have damage up here in the prideelobes,

52:25.640 --> 52:28.520
you sometimes lose your ability to direct your attention

52:28.520 --> 52:30.720
to different places in the visual scene.

52:30.720 --> 52:35.720
So that was approximately what was known in 1990.

52:35.720 --> 52:38.280
And here's what we know now.

52:38.280 --> 52:43.040
We now know, thanks largely to functional MRI,

52:43.080 --> 52:47.440
that for dozens of regions in the brain, in every one of you,

52:47.440 --> 52:51.520
we have a pretty good idea of the function of that region.

52:51.520 --> 52:53.480
This is major progress, right?

52:53.480 --> 52:57.120
This is a kind of rough sketch of the organization

52:57.120 --> 52:59.320
of the human mind and brain that we have now

52:59.320 --> 53:01.400
that we didn't have 20 years ago.

53:01.400 --> 53:04.480
And that's awesome.

53:04.480 --> 53:08.000
And so that has made possible a lot of progress

53:08.000 --> 53:09.640
building with other methods.

53:09.640 --> 53:12.840
And so what we'll study in this course

53:12.840 --> 53:15.000
is we'll focus on those mental functions

53:15.000 --> 53:18.040
where the brain bases are best understood.

53:18.040 --> 53:21.000
And that will include things like the visual perception

53:21.000 --> 53:24.280
of color, shape, and motion, visual recognition

53:24.280 --> 53:28.040
of faces, places, bodies, and words, and scenes.

53:28.040 --> 53:29.800
Didn't make it on the slide.

53:29.800 --> 53:30.560
Oh, yes, it did.

53:30.560 --> 53:33.880
Perceiving scenes and navigating.

53:33.880 --> 53:36.200
Understanding numbers.

53:36.200 --> 53:37.720
Yes, there's a whole lot about the brain

53:37.720 --> 53:39.560
bases of understanding numbers.

53:39.560 --> 53:42.920
Perceiving speech and perceiving music.

53:42.920 --> 53:45.000
Understanding language.

53:45.000 --> 53:48.720
Understanding other people and their minds.

53:48.720 --> 53:50.280
So those are the kinds of topics

53:50.280 --> 53:52.840
where there's been a lot of progress recently

53:52.840 --> 53:55.600
in understanding the brain bases of those mental functions.

53:55.600 --> 53:57.840
And so those are the ones we'll focus on.

53:57.840 --> 54:00.120
And that means there's going to be a lot on perception,

54:00.120 --> 54:03.960
high level vision, and high level audition.

54:03.960 --> 54:07.200
Because that's one where a lot of progress has been made,

54:07.200 --> 54:09.080
and it's also a lot of the cortex, right?

54:09.080 --> 54:11.280
As I mentioned a moment ago, the whole back third of your brain

54:11.280 --> 54:13.760
does vision, construed broadly.

54:13.760 --> 54:15.160
And so some people might say, why

54:15.160 --> 54:16.400
should spend all this time in vision?

54:16.400 --> 54:18.200
Well, it's like a big part of what your brain does.

54:18.200 --> 54:19.720
We are very visual animals, so we'll

54:19.720 --> 54:23.000
spend a lot of time on vision.

54:23.000 --> 54:26.280
OK, and so for each of these functions,

54:26.280 --> 54:30.280
we will ask, to what extent is this mental function implemented

54:30.280 --> 54:33.600
in its own specialized brain machinery?

54:33.600 --> 54:35.480
Are there multiple different brain regions

54:35.480 --> 54:38.320
that carry out that function?

54:38.320 --> 54:39.480
What does each one do?

54:39.480 --> 54:42.840
Is there a division of labor between those different regions?

54:42.840 --> 54:46.720
How does that system arise in development?

54:46.720 --> 54:49.840
How does it have homologs in other species?

54:49.840 --> 54:54.440
Are these things uniquely human, or which of them are?

54:54.440 --> 54:57.240
And also, along the way, other side cool questions

54:57.240 --> 54:59.320
that will come up.

54:59.320 --> 55:02.000
What if anything is special about the human brain?

55:02.000 --> 55:07.440
How come we are taking over and largely destroying the planet?

55:07.440 --> 55:10.080
And other species are not, right?

55:10.080 --> 55:11.680
Besides destroying the planet, we're

55:11.680 --> 55:14.280
doing some other cool things, like inventing science

55:14.280 --> 55:17.840
and engineering and medicine and architecture and poetry

55:17.840 --> 55:19.880
and literature and all these other music,

55:19.880 --> 55:23.200
all these other awesome things that other species aren't doing.

55:23.200 --> 55:27.040
How come our brains are doing that and other species aren't?

55:27.040 --> 55:28.960
Where does knowledge come from?

55:28.960 --> 55:30.960
You guys know all this stuff.

55:30.960 --> 55:33.400
How much of that stuff was wired in at birth?

55:33.400 --> 55:36.160
And how much of it did you get from experience?

55:39.200 --> 55:41.960
How much can our minds and brains change over time?

55:41.960 --> 55:44.200
Can we go study a new thing and get a whole new brain

55:44.200 --> 55:45.280
region for that thing?

55:48.640 --> 55:52.000
Can we change the basic structure just by training

55:52.000 --> 55:53.960
or after brain damage?

55:53.960 --> 55:56.920
Can we think without language?

55:56.920 --> 55:59.640
How many of you have wondered about that question?

55:59.640 --> 56:02.000
Yeah, really basic question.

56:02.000 --> 56:03.600
Anya's answering it.

56:03.600 --> 56:04.640
Anya and some others.

56:04.640 --> 56:06.720
But Anya's doing a lot to answer that question.

56:06.720 --> 56:09.040
There are actually empirical answers

56:09.040 --> 56:10.920
to these longstanding deep questions

56:10.920 --> 56:12.520
that everyone wonders about.

56:12.520 --> 56:13.120
That's pretty cool.

56:16.160 --> 56:18.680
Somebody back there asked a while ago about awareness.

56:18.680 --> 56:21.480
Can we think, perceive, understand without awareness?

56:21.480 --> 56:24.200
How much can go on, like in the basement of the brain,

56:24.200 --> 56:26.320
when we don't even know what's going on down there?

56:26.320 --> 56:29.000
We'll consider all of these other cool questions.

56:29.000 --> 56:29.600
OK.

56:29.600 --> 56:33.320
There's a bunch of things we won't cover in this course

56:33.320 --> 56:35.880
for various reasons that could have been in here and just

56:35.880 --> 56:36.280
aren't.

56:36.280 --> 56:37.720
There's only so much time.

56:37.720 --> 56:39.240
Motor control, it's really important

56:39.240 --> 56:40.880
to know how you do things like pick up

56:40.880 --> 56:43.240
objects and plan actions.

56:43.240 --> 56:46.200
And we're just not covering that.

56:46.200 --> 56:49.160
Something had to go.

56:49.160 --> 56:52.440
Subcortical function, this is a very corticocentric course.

56:52.440 --> 56:54.840
Most of the course will deal with the cortex.

56:54.840 --> 56:57.360
That's where most of conscious thinking and reasoning

56:57.360 --> 56:58.800
and cognition happens.

56:58.800 --> 57:00.920
There's a lot of good stuff down in the basement of the brain,

57:00.920 --> 57:03.600
and it's going to get pretty short shrift.

57:03.600 --> 57:06.440
Not for any good reason, just what it is.

57:06.440 --> 57:08.080
Decision making, important field,

57:08.080 --> 57:10.320
not getting much coverage in here.

57:10.320 --> 57:13.000
Importantly, circuit level mechanisms,

57:13.000 --> 57:15.320
explanations of cognition.

57:15.320 --> 57:17.800
If you think that we're going to understand not only what it

57:17.800 --> 57:19.880
means to understand the meaning of a sentence,

57:19.880 --> 57:22.840
but that I'm going to give you a wiring diagram of the neurons

57:22.840 --> 57:25.520
that implement that function, sorry to be

57:25.520 --> 57:28.720
the bearer of bad news, but nobody has a freaking clue

57:28.760 --> 57:30.480
how you could get a bunch of neurons

57:30.480 --> 57:32.800
to understand the meaning of a sentence.

57:32.800 --> 57:34.040
So that's exciting.

57:34.040 --> 57:36.240
That means there's a field for you guys to waltz into.

57:36.240 --> 57:37.720
And probably in your lifetimes, people

57:37.720 --> 57:40.200
will start to crack these things.

57:40.200 --> 57:42.760
But just to know what we're headed into,

57:42.760 --> 57:45.920
rarely, for almost no high-level mental functions,

57:45.920 --> 57:49.920
do we have anything like a wiring diagram level

57:49.920 --> 57:54.560
understanding of any perceptual or cognitive function.

57:54.560 --> 57:56.040
So that's not in the cards for this course,

57:56.040 --> 57:59.280
because it doesn't exist in the field.

57:59.280 --> 58:00.640
OK, for that kind of thing, there

58:00.640 --> 58:02.440
are cases where you can make progress.

58:02.440 --> 58:05.520
You can understand, say, fear conditioning in a mouse.

58:05.520 --> 58:08.720
Like, those circuits are being cracked wide open

58:08.720 --> 58:11.000
by people in this building, people all around the world

58:11.000 --> 58:13.080
with spectacular precision.

58:13.080 --> 58:15.160
They know the specific classes of neurons,

58:15.160 --> 58:16.400
their connectivity.

58:16.400 --> 58:18.120
They know every damn thing about them.

58:18.120 --> 58:19.960
But it's like, how does a mouse learn

58:19.960 --> 58:22.400
that this thing is to be afraid of this thing?

58:22.400 --> 58:23.560
OK, that's important.

58:23.560 --> 58:28.680
But for more complex aspects of cognition in humans,

58:28.680 --> 58:30.880
we can't usually have that kind of circuit level

58:30.880 --> 58:32.720
understanding.

58:32.720 --> 58:34.760
Lots of other things that will get short shrift.

58:34.760 --> 58:36.600
Memory, not for any good reason.

58:36.600 --> 58:40.080
I mean, there's a lot of coverage of memory in 900 and 901.

58:40.080 --> 58:42.440
And it's just somehow I've a blind spot for understanding.

58:42.440 --> 58:44.920
I've heard knowing how to talk interestingly about memory.

58:44.920 --> 58:46.960
So I'm not going to give you a boring lecture on memory.

58:46.960 --> 58:49.400
Instead, I'm not going to give you any lecture on memory

58:49.400 --> 58:52.480
till I learn how to talk about it interestingly.

58:52.480 --> 58:54.400
Reinforcement learning and reward systems,

58:54.400 --> 58:55.840
I'm going to try to pull some of that in.

58:55.840 --> 58:57.280
But it's not going to be a major focus,

58:57.280 --> 58:59.960
even though it's a really important part of cognition.

